          '@type': 'Question',
          name: 'Is RRM only for people who oppose IVF?',
          acceptedAnswer: {
            '@type': 'Answer',
            text: 'No. While some patients choose RRM for ethical or religious reasons, many pursue RRM because they want to understand and treat the underlying cause of their condition, not just achieve pregnancy. RRM appeals to patients who want a thorough diagnostic workup, who prefer to treat root causes before considering assisted reproduction, or who want to optimize their health regardless of family-building plans.',
          },
        },
        {
          '@type': 'Question',
          name: 'What training do RRM doctors have?',
          acceptedAnswer: {
            '@type': 'Answer',
            text: 'RRM physicians are typically board-certified OBGYNs or reproductive endocrinologists who pursue additional fellowship training in NaProTechnology or restorative reproductive medicine. Fellowship programs include training in the Creighton Model FertilityCare System, advanced hormonal evaluation, and specialized surgical techniques for conditions like endometriosis. RRM Academy offers courses for both patients and healthcare professionals seeking to deepen their understanding.',
          },
        },
      ],
    },
  ],
