---

<BaseLayout
  title="What is Restorative Reproductive Medicine (RRM)?"
  description="Restorative Reproductive Medicine (RRM) diagnoses and treats the root causes of reproductive health conditions rather than masking symptoms or bypassing natural function."
  canonicalUrl="https://rrmacademy.org/what-is-rrm"
  ogType="article"
  publishDate="2026-03-01"
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <div class="page-wrapper" data-pagefind-body>
    <div class="container container--narrow">

      <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <span aria-hidden="true"> &rsaquo; </span>
        <a href="/about/">About</a>
        <span aria-hidden="true"> &rsaquo; </span>
        <span>What is RRM?</span>
      </nav>

      <article class="prose">

        <h1>What is Restorative Reproductive Medicine (RRM)?</h1>

        <p class="author-byline">
          By <strong>Naomi Whittaker, MD</strong>, Board-Certified OBGYN and NaProTechnology Fellow &mdash; <time datetime="2026-03-01">March 2026</time>
        </p>

        <p><strong>Restorative Reproductive Medicine (RRM) is an approach within conventional medicine that works cooperatively with the body to diagnose and treat the underlying causes of reproductive health conditions.</strong> Unlike approaches that mask symptoms with hormonal medications or bypass natural function with assisted reproductive technologies, RRM uses standard and advanced diagnostic tools to investigate the root cause, whether hormonal, anatomical, or inflammatory, and restore natural function. Conditions commonly addressed include endometriosis, PCOS, infertility, recurrent miscarriage, and pelvic pain.</p>

        <h2>How RRM Works</h2>

        <p>RRM follows a diagnostic-first approach built on three principles:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Identify the root cause.</strong> Using cycle charting (such as the Creighton Model FertilityCare System), targeted bloodwork timed to the menstrual cycle, advanced imaging, and sometimes diagnostic surgery, RRM practitioners build a complete picture of what is going wrong and why.</li>
          <li><strong>Treat the underlying condition.</strong> Based on the diagnosis, treatment may include hormonal support (such as targeted progesterone supplementation), medication to address immune or inflammatory factors, or surgical intervention (such as excision surgery for endometriosis).</li>
          <li><strong>Restore natural function.</strong> The goal is not to bypass the reproductive system but to optimize it, addressing the condition so the body can function as intended, whether the patient's goal is fertility, symptom relief, or long-term health.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2>Conditions Commonly Treated with RRM</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Condition</th>
                <th>How RRM Approaches It</th>
                <th>Conventional Approach (for comparison)</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>Endometriosis</td>
                <td>Thorough diagnosis, excision surgery, long-term management plan</td>
                <td>Hormonal suppression (birth control), ablation surgery, IVF to bypass</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>PCOS</td>
                <td>Root-cause evaluation (insulin resistance, adrenal, inflammatory), targeted treatment</td>
                <td>Birth control to regulate cycles, metformin, Clomid/letrozole for fertility</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Unexplained infertility</td>
                <td>Advanced cycle-based diagnostics to identify previously missed causes</td>
                <td>Empiric treatment with IUI or IVF without identifying the cause</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Recurrent miscarriage</td>
                <td>Hormonal evaluation (progesterone, thyroid), immune factors, anatomical assessment</td>
                <td>Progesterone supplementation, IVF with PGT-A</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Irregular or painful periods</td>
                <td>Diagnostic workup to identify hormonal or structural cause, targeted treatment</td>
                <td>Hormonal birth control to suppress symptoms</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Pelvic pain</td>
                <td>Investigation for endometriosis, adhesions, or other structural causes</td>
                <td>Pain management, hormonal suppression</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p><em>This content is for educational purposes only and does not constitute medical advice. Consult a qualified healthcare provider for diagnosis and treatment.</em></p>

        <h2>RRM vs. IVF: Key Differences</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Factor</th>
                <th>RRM</th>
                <th>IVF</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>Approach</td>
                <td>Diagnose and treat root cause</td>
                <td>Bypass reproductive system</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Goal</td>
                <td>Restore natural function</td>
                <td>Achieve pregnancy</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Treats underlying condition?</td>
                <td>Yes</td>
                <td>No</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Typical cost per cycle</td>
                <td>Varies; often insurance-covered <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE]</mark></td>
                <td>$15,000&ndash;$30,000 per cycle <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE]</mark></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Multiple pregnancy risk</td>
                <td>Low (natural conception)</td>
                <td>Higher (especially with multiple embryo transfer)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Best suited for</td>
                <td>Treatable conditions (endometriosis, PCOS, hormonal issues)</td>
                <td>Tubal blockage, severe male factor, when time is critical</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Published live birth rates</td>
                <td>29&ndash;41% depending on age and diagnosis <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE]</mark></td>
                <td>~30&ndash;50% per cycle depending on age <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE]</mark></td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>These approaches are not always mutually exclusive. Some patients benefit from RRM treatment before pursuing assisted reproduction, and some RRM practitioners work alongside fertility specialists. <a href="/courses/rrm-vs-ivf/">Learn more in our free course: RRM vs. Standard ART</a>.</p>

        <h2>The Evidence Behind RRM</h2>

        <p>RRM is supported by peer-reviewed research published in journals including <em>Fertility and Sterility</em>, the <em>Journal of Restorative Reproductive Medicine</em>, and <em>BMC Pregnancy and Childbirth</em>. The <a href="https://library.rrmacademy.org">RRM Academy Research Library</a> contains 3,036+ peer-reviewed publications covering RRM outcomes, surgical techniques, hormonal protocols, and fertility awareness-based methods.</p>

        <p>Key findings from published research:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>RRM treatment followed by timed intercourse: 41% live birth rate <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE: JRRM 2021]</mark></li>
          <li>Surgical treatment of moderate-to-severe endometriosis: 55.3% pregnancy rate per woman <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE: meta-analysis]</mark></li>
          <li>RRM singletons had 3x fewer preterm deliveries compared to IVF <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE]</mark></li>
          <li>Average cost of RRM medication cycles was 20x less than IVF <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE]</mark></li>
        </ul>

        <p><em>Note: Outcomes vary by individual. All statistics represent published research averages, not guarantees. <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE specific studies before publishing]</mark></em></p>

        <h2>What is NaProTechnology?</h2>

        <p>NaProTechnology (Natural Procreative Technology) is a specific type of RRM developed at the Saint Paul VI Institute. It uses the Creighton Model FertilityCare System to track biomarkers across the menstrual cycle, enabling physicians to time diagnostic tests and treatments precisely. NaProTechnology is practiced by physicians with specialized fellowship training in medical and surgical techniques that cooperate with the reproductive system.</p>

        <p><a href="/courses/masterclass-in-endometriosis-and-surgery/">Learn from a NaProTechnology-trained surgeon: Masterclass in Endometriosis &amp; Surgery</a></p>

        <h2>How to Get Started with RRM</h2>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Learn the basics.</strong> <a href="/courses/">Browse free courses</a> on RRM Academy to understand the approach and what to expect.</li>
          <li><strong>Find a provider.</strong> Search the <a href="https://iirrm.org" rel="noopener">IIRRM provider directory</a> or <a href="https://www.fertilitycare.org" rel="noopener">FertilityCare Centers</a> for trained practitioners near you.</li>
          <li><strong>Explore the research.</strong> Browse the <a href="https://library.rrmacademy.org">RRM Research Library</a> with 3,036+ publications.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="cta-box">
          <h3>Ready to learn more?</h3>
          <p><a href="/courses/" class="btn btn--primary">Explore Free Courses</a></p>
          <p><a href="https://library.rrmacademy.org" class="btn btn--secondary">Browse the Research Library</a></p>
        </div>

      </article>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p class="page-updated">Last updated: March 2026</p>
</BaseLayout>

